Necromancers descend from the Entropy Scholars, independent practitioners who studied dissolution and decay in the margins of institutional frameworks — adjacent to the Great Pyramid's Black Sun Shard, in battlefield sites exceeding any institution's processing capacity, in abandoned cisterns where unclaimed bodies accumulated. The Psionicist academies branded them heretics when the Scholars' research into mental residue surviving death collided with the academies' jurisdictional claims. The Scholars' counter-argument — that death cannot be outlawed by institutional consensus — was correct in physical terms but institutionally ineffective. Three practical applications define the tradition: sustaining departed entities as operationally directed forces, drawing on residual spiritual energy as a power source before it dissipates, and weaponizing decay processes against living targets. All three carry theological opposition from cleric institutions, which argue that unauthorized sustaining of departed entities interferes with the cosmic accounting function that keeps the Black Sun Shard's memory-consuming effects contained. Necromancers whose engagement with this critique is honest find it neither conclusively refuted nor wholly convincing — the cleric tradition's argument depends on Solar Court institutional authority remaining legitimate, which is a complicated claim given the Court's centuries of inaccessibility. The Kinetimancer adept synthesis combines Necromancer entropy practice with Egomancer will-imposition, unified by the Kinetic Formulists' insight that both traditions redirect momentum: the necromantic variety redirects decay momentum toward specific targets, the egomantic variety redirects cognitive momentum toward practitioner-chosen outcomes.

