Rakuen's relationship with necromantic practice is filtered through the Ember Wardens' emergency doctrine: any practice that can contribute to communal survival under chronic emergency conditions has presumptive legitimacy, pending review of specific harms. Undead as labor units — clearing debris, maintaining structural elements, holding channels open during flood events — has been used in at least three documented Rakuen emergency episodes, always under Ember Warden supervision. The communal burden-sharing ethic creates ambivalence about necromantic practice because it can produce workers who do not share the burden: undead do not tire, do not need food allocation, do not occupy housing. Whether this is net positive (more labor capacity) or net negative (displacement of living workers from roles generating community participation) is genuinely contested. Necromancers in Rakuen must demonstrate that their practice contributes to collective survival, not merely individual capacity.

