Mafdet's Harbor Ledger House registers necromancers under the oath obligation system rather than the licensing compact model, which produces a different set of practical constraints. A necromancer in Mafdet swears an oath attesting their practice produces no unclaimed entities within harbor jurisdiction — any undead they create is their legal property and liability. The Swift Court's relevance: oath violations involving undead that damage harbor operations or cargo manifest integrity are treated as commercial fraud, not supernatural crime, producing faster adjudication. The Strandline Compact's governance structure gives maritime-adjacent necromancers specific obligations around drowned dead — bodies recovered from harbor waters fall under both the harbor ledger's jurisdiction and Khenari death-rite protocol, and a necromancer who raises a drowned sailor before the proper descent procedures are completed creates a multi-party liability dispute.

