Ushabti operate from a legal-verdict framework in which death is a completed adjudication — the cosmic claim has been assessed and the verdict rendered. Necromantic practice, from the Ushabti perspective, is an unauthorized appeal of a closed verdict: taking an entity whose case has been decided and returning it to active status without the claims process that would make such a reopening legitimate. In Midgaard, Ushabti engage with necromancers through the formal protest mechanism — filing challenges with the Office of Transitional Status Oversight arguing that undead entities have outstanding unsettled verdicts attached to them, creating liability for anyone who commands them. Ushabti necromancers are vanishingly rare, but when they exist they tend to frame their practice as verdict-enforcement: raising the dead to compel completion of unresolved claims before final closure.

