Khephari conceptualize death as a phase transition in an ongoing material cycle. Necromantic interruption of this cycle is a material problem: an entity that should be transitioning to substrate phase is instead held in an energetically anomalous state that the desert's material cycle cannot account for. In Midgaard's licensing compact context, Khephari practitioners who engage with necromancy tend to frame the practice in terms of controlled phase-arrest — maintaining an entity in transitional state for operational purposes before completing the cycle — rather than the theologically loaded language of resurrection or undeath. Khephari death-sense (their attunement to the physical processes of dissolution) gives them specific technical advantages in entropy practice: they can perceive the residual energy that Entropy Scholar doctrine identifies as the necromancer's power source with greater precision than practitioners lacking that attunement.

