Mafdet's Ushabti population is substantial — the city's judgment-and-balance mythology resonates with Ushabti legal-verdict framing — and Ushabti engagement with necromantic practice in Mafdet produces some of the most formally complex interactions between the harbor oath system and death-law. Ushabti necromancers in Mafdet are rare but not unknown: practitioners who frame their work as maintaining the dead in active status specifically to ensure unresolved claims can be adjudicated before final closure. The Shrine of the First Claw's oath-enforcement mechanisms are a congenial institutional context for Ushabti practitioners — the oath-enforcement process is itself a form of verdict mechanics. The Swift Court has produced at least two rulings on whether an undead entity under Ushabti necromantic direction retains legal standing sufficient to be a party to a commercial claim; both rulings declined to resolve the question definitively, citing insufficient precedent.

