Khenari in Kiess face Wall Command's operational metric without the theological buffer Midgaard's licensing compact provides. Wall Command assessors want to know what a necromancer can hold, not whether their practice violates the nine descents. A Khenari necromancer here experiences institutional demand stripped of the procedural framework that would give their theological discomfort a place to go — there is no Transitional Status Oversight Office filing that converts their practice into administratively acceptable form. Khenari communities in Kiess have developed informal internal protocols: a Khenari necromancer serving Wall Command roles is expected to maintain compressed descent records for each entity raised, completing whatever descent procedures can be performed and noting which cannot. The protocol has no official standing but is enforced socially within Khenari communities as the minimum necessary to maintain death-ledger integrity under frontier conditions.
